webpackJsonp([0x7fc4abe6700d],{326:function(e,t){e.exports={data:{post:{title:"Edition 35 (8/15/18)",content:'<p><span style="color:#000000">Hi there,<br />\r\n<br />\r\nHope you&#39;re having a better week than the Turks are. If you&#39;re a currency vigilante and don&#39;t mind some political turmoil, consider re-routing your late summer vacation to Ankara; your dollar will go pretty far right now.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nMore on that below.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p><img id="_x0000_i1025" src="https://gallery.mailchimp.com/fdc6c68021ff1ffb74a1c4fb1/images/bd8ad7b0-ee7d-40b2-8924-350cdb1df2e6.gif" style="-ms-interpolation-mode:bicubic; border-bottom-width:0in; border-left-width:0in; border-right-width:0in; border-top-width:0in; height:auto; max-width:736px; outline:none; text-decoration:none; vertical-align:bottom; width:564px" /></p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<h3 style="margin-left:0px; margin-right:0px"><span style="color:navy"><strong>Turkey at the Slaughter</strong></span></h3>\r\n\r\n<p><span style="color:black">The last time we discussed the impending breakdown of a foreign currency and economy, we tried not to blow things out of proportion. And low and behold, the Italian mini-crisis we referenced&nbsp;then hasn&#39;t materialized into a doomsday scenario for the EU.</span><br />\r\n<br />\r\n<span style="color:black">We&#39;ll try to keep the same levelheadedness now as it relates to Turkey. Per the above chart (source <a href="https://siyucapital.us18.list-manage.com/track/click?u=fdc6c68021ff1ffb74a1c4fb1&amp;id=617b7fe27b&amp;e=b7c527e94b" style="-ms-text-size-adjust:100%; -webkit-text-size-adjust:100%" target="_blank"><span style="color:#00add8">here</span></a>), you can see how the price of a 5-year Credit Default Swap - a contract comparable to insurance that pays out if Turkey defaults on government debt payments - has gone moon bound since the end of May. It is also well above the price of an Argentinian CDS, which has had a bit of a&nbsp;<a href="https://siyucapital.us18.list-manage.com/track/click?u=fdc6c68021ff1ffb74a1c4fb1&amp;id=3968db8a01&amp;e=b7c527e94b" style="-ms-text-size-adjust:100%; -webkit-text-size-adjust:100%" target="_blank"><span style="color:#00add8">currency crisis</span></a> of its own so far this year. </span><br />\r\n<br />\r\n<span style="color:black">The trigger for the Turkish&nbsp;troubles was a fresh-slate of US economic sanctions, as described by the New York Times:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<div style="background:#eeeeee; border:1px solid #cccccc; padding:5px 10px"><span style="color:#000000">&quot;The object is to force the Turkish president, Recep Tayyip Erdogan, to release Andrew Brunson, an American and evangelical Christian pastor who has been imprisoned by Turkey since 2016 on trumped-up charges of aiding an aborted coup by Erdogan opponents.&quot;</span></div>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;<span style="color:black">At the beginning of this&nbsp;week Erdogan </span><span style="color:gray"><a href="https://siyucapital.us18.list-manage.com/track/click?u=fdc6c68021ff1ffb74a1c4fb1&amp;id=30e02823e2&amp;e=b7c527e94b" style="-ms-text-size-adjust: 100%;-webkit-text-size-adjust: 100%" target="_blank"><span style="color:black">reiterated</span></a></span><span style="color:black"> that his nation was not interested in acquiescing to US demands, nor in an international bailout.&nbsp;</span><br />\r\n<br />\r\n<span style="color:black">All this political posturing is more of a catalyst than a cause however.&nbsp;Turkey was already in a precarious financial situation pre-sanctions, having accumulated significant debt to pursue economic growth at all costs in recent years. See below for more on that (source, <a href="https://siyucapital.us18.list-manage.com/track/click?u=fdc6c68021ff1ffb74a1c4fb1&amp;id=97bbe6f4e1&amp;e=b7c527e94b" style="-ms-text-size-adjust: 100%;-webkit-text-size-adjust: 100%" target="_blank"><span style="color:#0066cc">again</span></a>):</span><span style="color:gray"> </span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><img id="_x0000_i1025" src="https://gallery.mailchimp.com/fdc6c68021ff1ffb74a1c4fb1/images/2b88d4be-fa5e-4930-baa1-750213867590.jpg" style="-ms-interpolation-mode:bicubic; border-bottom-width:0in; border-left-width:0in; border-right-width:0in; border-top-width:0in; display:inline; height:auto; max-width:622px; outline:none; padding-bottom:0in; text-decoration:none; vertical-align:bottom; width:564px" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style="color:black">With this heavy foreign debt load, and given how rapidly the lira has sold off&nbsp;in relation to the dollar, it&#39;s becoming increasingly likely the Turkish government won&#39;t be able to make debt payments (hence the rise in the value of Credit Default Swaps on Turkish government bonds which we began the article with).<br />\r\n<br />\r\nSince hitting a record low FX rate of 7.22 against the dollar (aka 1 lira buys you ~ .14 dollars, <a href="https://siyucapital.us18.list-manage.com/track/click?u=fdc6c68021ff1ffb74a1c4fb1&amp;id=aa37a2e85d&amp;e=b7c527e94b" style="-ms-text-size-adjust: 100%;-webkit-text-size-adjust: 100%" target="_blank"><span style="color:#00add8">chart</span></a>&nbsp;at end of this section), the lira has stabilized somewhat as the Turkish Central Bank said it would ease reserve requirements on banks. The US equity markets&nbsp;posted 4 consecutive days of losses last week and Monday, and are in the red again today.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nMeanwhile, Turkish equities are hitting decade lows. The net result of foreign weakness is that investors are <a href="https://siyucapital.us18.list-manage.com/track/click?u=fdc6c68021ff1ffb74a1c4fb1&amp;id=cb29a17b0b&amp;e=b7c527e94b" style="-ms-text-size-adjust: 100%;-webkit-text-size-adjust: 100%" target="_blank"><span style="color:#00add8">piling even more heavily into US </span></a>equities as opposed to Emerging Markets. Per FT and a Bank of America global fund manager survey, the below quote highlights prevailing market sentiments, some of which&nbsp;we have belabored at length:</span><span style="color:gray"> </span></p>\r\n\r\n<div style="background:#eeeeee; border:1px solid #cccccc; padding:5px 10px"><span style="color:#000000">&quot;The most crowded trade, for the seventh straight month, was in the FAANG and BAT stocks (Facebook, Amazon, Apple, Netflix, Google, and Baidu, Alibaba, Tencent); shorting US Treasuries was the third most crowded trade, offering further evidence of the widespread anticipation in the markets of a positive US growth narrative.&quot;</span></div>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;<img id="_x0000_i1025" src="https://gallery.mailchimp.com/fdc6c68021ff1ffb74a1c4fb1/images/5504d679-8a6a-4f41-be5c-0557b6699d22.jpg" style="-ms-interpolation-mode:bicubic; border-bottom-width:0in; border-left-width:0in; border-right-width:0in; border-top-width:0in; display:inline; height:auto; max-width:800px; outline:none; padding-bottom:0in; text-decoration:none; vertical-align:bottom; width:564px" /></p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p style="margin-left:0px; margin-right:0px"><strong><span style="color:navy">Pet Rock Problems</span></strong><br />\r\n<br />\r\n<span style="color:black">Gold continues to get hit hard, breaching the $1,200 marker for the first time </span><span style="color:gray"><a href="https://siyucapital.us18.list-manage.com/track/click?u=fdc6c68021ff1ffb74a1c4fb1&amp;id=7bb6aedf6e&amp;e=b7c527e94b" style="-ms-text-size-adjust:100%; -webkit-text-size-adjust:100%" target="_blank"><span style="color:black">since July, 2017</span></a></span><span style="color:black">. The stronger dollar represents a significant headwind for the gold price at current. As explained far more succinctly than we would have per the above linked article:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<div style="background:#eeeeee; border:1px solid #cccccc; padding:5px 10px">\r\n<p style="margin-left:0px; margin-right:0px"><span style="color:black">&quot;A higher U.S. currency also makes dollar-denominated assets more expensive for holders of other currencies, which subdues demand - a relationship used by funds to generate buy and sell signals from numerical models.&quot;</span></p>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0px; margin-right:0px"><span style="color:black">Investors broadly are capitulating to the trend. See below for a chart detailing the strong tide of funds flowing out of gold in recent weeks.</span><span style="color:gray"> </span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0px; margin-right:0px"><span style="color:gray"><img id="_x0000_i1025" src="https://gallery.mailchimp.com/fdc6c68021ff1ffb74a1c4fb1/images/b1ab5941-9a44-4019-9fc2-edb7f3309176.png" style="-ms-interpolation-mode:bicubic; border-bottom-width:0in; border-left-width:0in; border-right-width:0in; border-top-width:0in; display:inline; height:auto; max-width:800px; outline:none; padding-bottom:0in; text-decoration:none; vertical-align:bottom; width:564px" /></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0px; margin-right:0px"><span style="color:black">There&nbsp;remains the historically well-documented and ever present question of why anyone values gold in the first place, which is not something we&#39;re prepared to thoughtfully address right now. It does have some of the key characteristics of viable currency, including divisibility, ease of exchange, portability and durability. But so do a lot of other things.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<a href="https://siyucapital.us18.list-manage.com/track/click?u=fdc6c68021ff1ffb74a1c4fb1&amp;id=eb67fba586&amp;e=b7c527e94b" style="-ms-text-size-adjust: 100%;-webkit-text-size-adjust: 100%" target="_blank"><span style="color:#00add8">When asked</span></a> why the Federal Reserve still holds massive gold stockpiles, Ben Bernanke famously answered &quot;Tradition...long term tradition.&quot;</span><span style="color:gray"> </span></p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p><span style="color:navy"><strong>From Slumbering VIX to Rumbling VIX</strong></span><br />\r\n<br />\r\n<span style="color:black">Last week we mentioned that the S&amp;P 500 volatility index - the VIX - had retreated to lows not seen since January before the market sell-off that has colored a lot of the conversation regarding markets this year. </span><br />\r\n<br />\r\n<span style="color:black">We have again apparently jinxed things, as the VIX clamored its way back up to a high of 16.68 this morning. That&#39;s a 50% + premium to the values seen last week. What does it mean? Principally it indicates stock options market-wide are more expensive currently given enhanced volatility projections. </span></p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p><img id="_x0000_i1025" src="https://gallery.mailchimp.com/fdc6c68021ff1ffb74a1c4fb1/images/d3f8b733-0b05-4dc7-b594-29fb0125ca97.jpg" style="-ms-interpolation-mode:bicubic; border-bottom-width:0in; border-left-width:0in; border-right-width:0in; border-top-width:0in; height:auto; max-width:696px; outline:none; text-decoration:none; vertical-align:bottom; width:564px" /></p>\r\n\r\n<div style="background:#eeeeee; border:1px solid #cccccc; padding:5px 10px"><span style="color:#000000">Here&#39;s our parting chart for the day. It isn&#39;t inherently investing related, but it shows that since 2014, the life expectancy of the average US citizen has declined. Not a happy chart, to say the least.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nWhile this remains more of a general interest topic, it bears remembering that demographic trends affect capital markets as well. A less healthy populous is costly economically not just in terms of the healthcare infrastructure, but in terms of worker productivity as well.</span></div>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p><span style="color:#000000">&nbsp;<strong>Adios.</strong><br />\r\n<br />\r\nKeep reaching out to us with feedback, questions, or future topics you&#39;d like to here more about. Those of you that have can vouch for our responsiveness.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nN + M</span></p>',updated:"2018-08-15T17:35:39.685604Z",fields:{slug:"Edition-35",date:"(8/15/18)"}}},pathContext:{slug:"Edition-35"}}}});
//# sourceMappingURL=path---edition-35-88731b2bb41cbae9becc.js.map